\begin_layout Subsection

\lang french
Extraction du potentiel
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang french
A l'aide de la bibliothèque Python BEMPP 
\begin_inset Formula $(Boundary Element Method Python Package)$
\end_inset

, on peut extraire le potentiel 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi ({\color{red}r},{\color{blue}\theta},{\color{green}z})$
\end_inset

 en tout point de l'espace. Comme vu dans la partie précédente, il est important de décomposer le potentiel afin de pouvoir séparer la contribution des différents ordres. Une fois le potentiel extrait, il faut donc trouver les différentes composantes de la décomposition du potentiel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\lang french
Composantes multipolaires
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection

\lang french
Equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang french
On peut retouver les composantes multipolaires à l'aide de la formule 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Phi_{\nu}= \frac{2-\delta_{0\nu}}{\nu!}\left.
(\frac{\partial^{\nu} \phi}{\partial \bar w^{\nu}})
\right|_{ w=0}.
\]
\end_inset

où 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 est l'ordre du terme multipolaire et 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{0\nu}$
\end_inset

 le symbole de Kronecker. 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Pour un développement limité à l'ordre 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 en 
\begin_inset Formula ${\color{red}r}$
\end_inset

, les valeurs admissibles de 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 sont déterminées par la condition 
\begin_inset Formula \[
2\lambda + \nu \le N
\]
\end_inset

Dans le cadre de ce travail, on se limite à 
\begin_inset Formula $N=4$
\end_inset

 et 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu \le 2$
\end_inset

, ce qui conduit aux valeurs suivantes : 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda = 0,1,2$
\end_inset

 pour 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=0$
\end_inset

 et 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda = 0,1$
\end_inset

 pour 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=1,2$
\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 On peut alors calculer les différents ordres des composantes multipolaires: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\lang french
Cas 
\begin_inset Formula \(\nu = 0\)
\end_inset

 (monopôle)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang french

\begin_inset space \space{}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 On a 
\begin_inset Formula \(\delta_{00} = 1\)
\end_inset

, d'où 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Phi_0(z) = \frac{2 - \delta_{00}}{0!} \left. \frac{\partial^{0} \phi}{\partial \bar{w}^{0}} \right|_{w=0} = \phi(x, y, z)\big|_{w=0}.
\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\lang french
Cas 
\begin_inset Formula \(\nu = 1\)
\end_inset

 (dipôle)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang french

\begin_inset space \space{}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 On a 
\begin_inset Formula \(\delta_{01} = 0\)
\end_inset

, d'où 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Phi_1(z) = \frac{2 - \delta_{01}}{1!} \left. \left( \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial \bar{w}} \right) \right|_{w=0} = 2 \left. \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial \bar{w}} \right|_{w=0}.
\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\lang french
Cas 
\begin_inset Formula \(\nu = 2\)
\end_inset

 (quadrupôle)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang french

\begin_inset space \space{}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 On a 
\begin_inset Formula \(\delta_{02} = 0\)
\end_inset

, d'où 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Phi_2(z) = \frac{2 - \delta_{02}}{2!} \left. \frac{\partial^{2} \phi}{\partial \bar{w}^{2}} \right|_{w=0} = \frac{1}{2} \left. \frac{\partial^{2} \phi}{\partial \bar{w}^{2}} \right|_{w=0}.
\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\lang french
Cas 
\begin_inset Formula \(\nu = 3\)
\end_inset

 (hexapôle)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang french

\begin_inset space \space{}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 On a 
\begin_inset Formula \(\delta_{03} = 0\)
\end_inset

, d'où 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Phi_3(z) = \frac{2 - \delta_{03}}{3!} \left. \frac{\partial^{3} \phi}{\partial \bar{w}^{3}} \right|_{w=0} = \frac{1}{3} \left. \frac{\partial^{3} \phi}{\partial \bar{w}^{3}} \right|_{w=0}.
\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\lang french
Cas 
\begin_inset Formula \(\nu = 4\)
\end_inset

 (octopôle)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang french

\begin_inset space \space{}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 On a 
\begin_inset Formula \(\delta_{04} = 0\)
\end_inset

, d'où 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Phi_4(z) = \frac{2 - \delta_{04}}{4!} \left. \frac{\partial^{4} \phi}{\partial \bar{w}^{4}} \right|_{w=0} = \frac{1}{12} \left. \frac{\partial^{4} \phi}{\partial \bar{w}^{4}} \right|_{w=0}.
\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\lang french
Cas général
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang french

\begin_inset space \space{}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 On obtient finalement avec 
\begin_inset Formula \(\bar{w} = x - iy\)
\end_inset

 et 
\begin_inset Formula \(\frac{\partial}{\partial \bar{w}} = \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial x} + i\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\right)\)
\end_inset

 que
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang french

\begin_inset Formula \[
\begin{aligned}
\Phi_0(z) &= \phi(x, y, z)\big|_{x=y=0}, \\[0.4em]
\Phi_1(z) &= \left. \left( \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial x} + i \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial y} \right) \right|_{x=y=0}, \\[0.6em]
\Phi_2(z) &= \left. \frac{1}{8} \left( \frac{\partial^{2} \phi}{\partial x^{2}} - \frac{\partial^{2} \phi}{\partial y^{2}} - 2i \frac{\partial^{2} \phi}{\partial x \partial y} \right) \right|_{x=y=0}, \\[0.6em]
\Phi_3(z) &= \left. \frac{1}{24} \left( \frac{\partial^{3} \phi}{\partial x^{3}} - 3 \frac{\partial^{3} \phi}{\partial x \partial y^{2}} - 3i \frac{\partial^{3} \phi}{\partial x^{2} \partial y} + i \frac{\partial^{3} \phi}{\partial y^{3}} \right) \right|_{x=y=0}, \\[0.6em]
\Phi_4(z) &= \left. \frac{1}{192} \left( \frac{\partial^{4} \phi}{\partial x^{4}} - 6 \frac{\partial^{4} \phi}{\partial x^{2} \partial y^{2}} + \frac{\partial^{4} \phi}{\partial y^{4}} - 4i \frac{\partial^{4} \phi}{\partial x^{3} \partial y} + 4i \frac{\partial^{4} \phi}{\partial x \partial y^{3}} \right) \right|_{x=y=0}.
\end{aligned}
\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang french
Ici, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{\nu} \phi}{\partial \bar w^{\nu}}$
\end_inset

 représente la dérivée d'ordre 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 du potentiel par rapport à la coordonnée transverse 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 évaluée sur l'axe central 
\begin_inset Formula $w=0$
\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset space \space{}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 Comme dans le cas de notre code, on choisit le référentiel (x,y) tel qu'un cosinus décrit le quadrupole. On peut donc écrire: 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\begin{aligned}
\Phi_0(z) &= \phi(x,y,z)\big|_{x=y=0} \\[1em]
\Phi_1(z) &=\left.\left(\frac{\partial \phi}{\partial x}\right)\right|_{x=y=0} \\[1em]
\Phi_2(z) &=\left.\frac{1}{8}\left(\frac{\partial^{2} \phi}{\partial x^{2}}-\frac{\partial^{2} \phi}{\partial y^{2}}\right)\right|_{x=y=0} \\[1em]
\Phi_3(z) &=\left.\frac{1}{24}\left(\frac{\partial^{3} \phi}{\partial x^{3}}-3 \frac{\partial^{3} \phi}{\partial x \partial y^{2}}\right)\right|_{x=y=0} \\[1em]
\Phi_4(z) &=\left.\frac{1}{192}\left(\frac{\partial^{4} \phi}{\partial x^{4}}-6 \frac{\partial^{4} \phi}{\partial x^{2} \partial y^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{4} \phi}{\partial y^{4}}\right)\right|_{x=y=0}
\end{aligned}
\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

